Module kivakit.core.collections
Package com.telenav.kivakit.core.collections.primitive.array.packed

Class PackedArray

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.telenav.kivakit.core.collections.primitive.PrimitiveCollection
      • com.telenav.kivakit.core.collections.primitive.array.PrimitiveArray
        • com.telenav.kivakit.core.collections.primitive.array.packed.PackedArray
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.esotericsoftware.kryo.KryoSerializable, PackedPrimitiveArray, LongIterable, LongList, PrimitiveList, LongCollection, Initializable, NamedObject, Countable, Sized, CompressibleCollection
    public final class PackedArray
extends PrimitiveArray
implements LongList, PackedPrimitiveArray
    A packed array packs arbitrary bit-length integral values into an underlying long array.

    For example, if you create a packed array of 3-bit values, the first three bits of the first long (at index 0) in the long array would store the first 3-bit value, the next 3 bits would store the second 3-bit value, and so on... until we get to value 21, which would span from the first long to the second one and be stored in the last bit of the first long and the first two bits of the second long (because 64 / 3 = 21 and 21 * 3 = 63, leaving only one bit left in the first long). In diagram form, the long array will be laid out like this: 

     long array: [----------- index 0 -------------------]   [---------- index 1 ---------]
     values: [ value 0 ]   [ value 1 ]  ... [value 20]   [value 21]
       bit: 0    1    2   3    4    5  ... 60  61  62   63   0   1

    A special null value can be specified by passing a nullValue to the constructor. When this particular numeric value is read by get(int) and safeGet(int), they will return null instead of that value. When a null reference is passed to set(int, long), it will be stored as the given null numeric value.

    Author:
    jonathanl (shibo)
